title: -The (N,2N) Excitation Functions for 41-Nb-93 and 45-Rh-103 With Special Respect To The Isomeric States In 41-Nb-92 and 45-Rh-102.-

x4codes.shortRef: Jour: Zeitschrift fuer Physik, Vol.238, p.23 (1970)

x4freetext: -THE (N,2N) EXCITATION FUNCTIONS FOR 41-NB-93 AND
45-RH-103 WITH SPECIAL RESPECT TO THE ISOMERIC STATES
3 MEV VAN DE GRAAFF OF THE CBNM.
N15(D,N)-REACTION AT E(D) = 1.8 MEV FOR E(N)
FROM 10.26 TO 11.53 MEV. THE TARGET WAS 2 MILLIGR/CM2
OF SI(3)-N(4) (N15 ENRICHED).
T(D,N)-REACTION AT E(D) = 1.0 MEV FOR E(N)
FROM 12.61 TO 16.07 MEV USING THE TARGET OF 1 MILLIGR/
CM2,AND AT E(D) = 3.0 MEV FOR E(N) FROM 16.18 TO
19.59 MEV USING THE TARGET OF 2.8 MILLIGR/CM2 TI-T.
.METALLIC SAMPLE OF 20 MM DIAMETER AND 5MM
THICKNESS.
TWO GE(LI) PLANAR DIODES OF THE ORDER OF
1 CM**3 VOLUME FOR ACTIVATION MEASUREMENT.
PROTON RECOIL TELESCOPE COUNTER AT 0 DEG
RELATIVE TO THE DEUTERON BEAM WAS USED TO MEASURE THE
NEUTRON FLUX(ABSOLUTE).
.THE RELATIVE N-FLUX FOR SAMPLE WAS DEDUCED FROM
ANGULAR DISTRIBUTION MEASUREMENTS BY NEUTRON TOF
SPECTROMETER FOR (D-N15) REACTION AND BY A PROTON
RECOIL TELESCOPE COUNTER FOR (D-T) REACTION.
A NE 102A PLASTIC SCINTILLATOR WITH AVP-
56/03 PHOTOMULTIPLIER FOR TOF EXPERIMENT.
PHOTOPEAKS OF THE PULSE HEIGHT SPECTRA WERE
USED.
.RADIOACTIVITY OF 10.15 DAY(ISOMERIC STATE) WAS MEASUR-
ED TO DETERMINE THE 41-NB-93(N,2N)41-NB-92-M1
CROSS-SECTION.
.ABSOLUTE MEASUREMENT.
.THE NEUTRON FLUX WAS MEASURED BY PROTON RECOIL TELE-
SCOPE COUNTER.
.THE CALIBRATION SOURCES OF CO-58 AND NA-22 WERE USED
TO MEASURE THEIR ACTIVITIES WITH +- 1 PER CENT
ACCURACY. THE SOURCES CONSISTED OF AN ACTIVE FOIL OF
19 MM DIAMETER ENCLOSED IN A STAINLESS STEEL HAUSING
OF 20 MM DIAMETER AND 1 MM THICKNESS.
.THE CALIBRATION SOURCES WERE SANDWICHED BETWEEN TWO
DISKS OF 20 MM DIAMETER AND 2 MM THICKNESS OF STAIN-
LESS STEEL TO ADJUST THE GAMMA ABSORPTION COEFFICIENT
OF THE SOURCES TO THAT OF THE SAMPLE.
.UP TO NOW NO RADIOACTIVE DECAY OF THE GROUND STATE OF
41-NB-92 COULD BE DETECTED.ALL EXISTING (N,2N) ACTIVA-
TION MEASUREMENTS REPRESENT ONLY A PART OF THE (N,2N)
TOTAL CROSS SECTION. SEE H.B.CARTER, 66WASH P682.
.DATA FROM TABLE 1 OF Z.PHYSIK 238 P.27.
.A CORRECTION FACTOR OF GAMMA-DETECTION WAS DETERMINED
FOR THE CENTER POSITION OF THE SOURCE BY VARYING ITS
POSITION IN DIFFERENT SANDWICHES.
.THE TOTAL UNCERTAINTY IN PARTIAL CROSS-SECTION RANGES
FROM +- 5 TO 8 PER CENT.
.NEUTRON ENERGY SPREADS DUE TO TARGET THICKNESS AND
SAMPLE SOLID ANGLE ARE GIVEN.

x4freetext: FLIGHT PATH = 1.4 M.
.A PULSED ION BEAM OF 1 NS PULSE WIDTH AND 1 MHZ
REPETITION.
.OVERALL TIME RESOLUTION IS ABOUT 2.3 NS.
.EACH MEASUREMENT CONSISTS OF A LARGE NUMBER OF ALTER-
NATING   SAMPLE IN   AND   SAMPLE OUT   RUNS TO
SUBTRACT THE BACKGROUND.
.THE TOF SPECTRA CONTAINED ONLY VERY WEAK ELASTIC PEAKS
BUT RELATIVE STRONG PROMPT GAMMA PEAKS WHICH WERE USED
FOR THE TIME-TO-ENERGY TRANSFORMATION.
.TOF FLIGHT PATH OF 1.4 M FORMS AN ANGLE OF 90 DEG WITH
THE DIRECTION OF THE INCOMING NEUTRONS.
.HEAVY LEAD SHIELD WAS USED BETWEEN TARGET AND DETECTOR
.THE OBTAINED N-SPECTRA FROM THE TOF MEASURE-
MENT WERE FITTED BY THE LEAST SQUARE METHOD TO    F(E)
= C*E*EXP(-E/T)   ON BOTH CO AND NB SAMPLES, AS AN
APPROXIMATION TO A NUCLEAR EVAPORATION SPECTRUM.
.CROSS SECTION OF 27-CO-59(N,2N) OF 780 MB AT E(N)=16.8
MEV WAS USED.
.THE SMALL CONTRIBUTIONS FROM (N,N ) AND (N,PN) IN THE
TOTAL NB-93(N,2N) CROSS-SECTION ARE NOT SEVERE.
.PRESENT CROSS-SECTION VALUE AT 16.8 MEV WAS COMPARED
WITH THE ONLY EXISTING VALUE OF 1136 MB AT 14.7 MEV BY
H.B.CARTER,66WASH P682.
.THE EXPERIMENTAL TOTAL (N,2N) CROSS-SECTION IS ABOUT
20 PER CENT SMALLER THAN THE THEORETICAL ONE FROM THE
STATISTICAL MODEL CALCULATION. THIS DISCREPANCY CAN BE
EXPLAINED BY THE UNCERTAINTY OF THE LEVEL DENSITY
PARAMETERS  A  AND  B . H.LISKIEN, A.PAULSEN,65ANTWERP
.DATA FROM P.28 OF Z.PHYSIK 238.
.IN COMPARISON OF THE N-YIELDS OF NB AND CO,THE SLIGHT-
LY DIFFERENT NUCLEAR TEMPERATURES WERE TAKEN INTO
ACCOUNT WHICH GAVE RISE OF A 3 PER CENT CORRECTION.

.BETWEEN TWO DIFFERENT HALF-LIFES FOR THE DECAY OF RH-

STATE.  P.BORN ETAL, PHYSICA 29(1963)535, AND M.ADACHI
